passages.text: Flickering - FY25 Result

Despite the sales momentum seen in 4Q25 and early FY26, comp sales growth needs to accelerate from \(1.5\%\) (vs pcp) to mid single digit \(\%\) to hit consensus/JPM estimates for 1H26 (JPMe 1H26 sales growth \(\sim 3.5\%\) ). Interest rate cuts and improving consumer sentiment provide a tailwind in the near term, however guidance of two new store openings (below targeted pace of 3 to 5 net store additions) has led us to moderate expectations for FY26. Increases to CODB are expected to be addressed by management, while continued growth in Trade delivers operating leverage in a recovering R&R market. Remain OW. PT A\ \(3.55. \)

- Momentum into FY26. Comp sales growth accelerated through FY25 (1H25 comp sales \(+1.3\%\) , FY25 comp sales \(+1.5\%\) , implies 2H25 \(-1.7\%\) ), with increasing sales momentum in 4Q25. Management commented that improvement in 4Q was seen across both retail and trade segments and across states (incl Victoria), with further interest rate cuts and improving consumer confidence to support the near term outlook. We suspect comp sales growth will need to accelerate to MSD \(\%\) to meet cons/JPM estimates (1H26 JPMe sales growth \(\sim 3.5\%\) ). Further, BLX has guided to 2 new store openings in FY26, with other stores under consideration (JPMe \(+3\) net store additions) which is below the targeted pace of openings (3 to 5 net store additions p.a.).

- Cost management and cash flow. Cost pressures weighed on the FY25 result with 2H25 CODB \(\%\) sales of \(44.7\%\) (up 31bps vs pcp and above FY25 CODB \(\%\) of \(43.5\%\) ). While the step-up in 2H CODB expenses is part of BLX's typical seasonality, wage pressures were highlighted by management as being a significant driver of the \(5.3\%\) increase in opex vs pcp. Management has undertaken initiatives to address costs with a stabilization expected in FY26. Cash conversion was solid with GOFC in line with EBITDA, but worth noting there was a slight inventory build offset by an increase in payables.

- Trade growth offsetting subdued retail channel. Momentum continued across trade channels, with store trade sales \(+24\%\) vs pcp \((+25\%\) at 1H25 results) and now comprising \(40\%\) of sales. Beacon Trade online visitation and online sales increased \(+27\%\) and \(+29\%\) respectively, with the company on track to achieve the goal of \(50\%\) trade sales by FY28. We remain constructive on BLX's push into the trade segment, which we believe will position the company to deliver operating leverage on a recovery in construction and renovation activity.

- Earnings and valuation. Our FY26/27 earnings estimates (NPAT \(-4\% / - 5\%\) ) reflect a moderation in comp store sales and store rollout growth assumptions for FY26. We assume relatively stable gross margins in FY26/27 on the back of beneficial factory pricing with opex pressures to be offset by scale and cost efficiencies. We have rolled-forward our model to Jun-26 and pushed out our store rollout assumptions to later years. We remain OW. PT -1.4\% to A\\(3.55 per share.

Investment ThesisBeacon Lighting is a leading Australian specialist retailer of lighting, ceiling fans, and light globes, operating over 120 stores across Australia serving both the B2C and Trade segments. BLX has a vertically-integrated operating model, whereby 95% of lighting and fan products are supplied through the BLX supply-chain, and more than 85% of products are exclusively branded. We see upside driven by further growth into the trade segment towards BLX's 50/50 target by FY28, and a cyclical recovery in renovation activity as the macro backdrop improves. Maintain OW.

ValuationOur Jun- 26 price target of A\(3.55 per share is driven by our DCF- based valuation (WACC: 9.0%; forecast period: 10 years; terminal value: assumes the company does not generate ROIC above WACC in perpetuity). Our share price target is based on the future value of our valuation, less any dividends to be paid between now and the target date.

BLX provided the below outlook commentary:

Sales momentum increased in 4Q25 and has continued into the start of FY26, including momentum in trade sales.- FY26 store rollout plan includes 2 planned stores, noting other stores are under consideration (JPME of 3 net store additions).- No change to 'long term store network opportunity' (195 stores in Australia).

Following the result, we have adjusted our earnings forecasts as detailed in the table below. Our FY26/27 NPAT revisions (- 4%/- 5%) reflect a moderation in comp store sales and store rollout growth assumptions for FY26. We assume relatively stable gross margins in FY26/27 on the back of beneficial factory pricing with open pressures to be offset by scale and cost efficiencies. We have rolled-forward our model to Jun- 26 and pushed out our store rollout assumptions to later years. We remain OW. PT AS3.55 per share.

Beacon Lighting (Overweight; Price Target: A\(3.55)

Beacon Lighting is a leading Australian specialist retailer of lighting, ceiling fans, and light globes, operating over 120 stores across Australia serving both the B2C and Trade segments. BLX has a vertically- integrated operating model, whereby \(95\%\) of lighting and fan products are supplied through the BLX supply- chain, and more than \(85\%\) of products are exclusively branded. We see upside driven by further growth into the trade segment towards BLX's 50/50 target by FY28, and a cyclical recovery in renovation activity as the macro backdrop improves. Maintain OW.

Our Jun- 26 price target of A\(3.55 per share is driven by our DCF- based valuation (WACC: \(9.0\%\) ; forecast period: 10 years; terminal value: assumes the company does not generate ROIC above WACC in perpetuity).
